Trip Generation Analysis - American Academy (Motsenbocker Road Site) -------- 7
The American Academy is proposing a new K–8 charter school to be located in the Town of
Parker, Colorado. At build out, the school would accommodate approximately 900 students. The
school site, currently vacant, is located along the west side of Motsenbocker Road, to the south
of Mainstreet. Figure 1 illustrates the location of the site and the adjacent roadway network.
The school would have vehicular access via Motsenbocker Road, an existing two-lane collector
roadway that extends between Clarke Farms Drive on the north and Stroh Road on the south.
Two site accesses are proposed: the primary school access would be located approximately
650 feet south of Paoli Way, with a secondary (emergency only) access located approximately
200 feet south of Paoli Way. The on-site circulation system would serve parking and student
drop-off activity, with provision for anticipated on-site vehicle queues. Figure 2 depicts the
The purpose of this traffic study is to estimate the potential impacts specific to the American
Academy Charter School and to identify any resultant required roadway or traffic control
improvements. Two future planning horizons were evaluated:
 Short Range Future. The proposed American Academy Charter School is expected to
be operational by 2014. The short range future scenario examines the impact that
school-generated traffic would have on an “opening day” scenario.
 Long Range Future. A long range (year 2030) planning horizon was evaluated for the
site. This planning horizon is consistent with the Town of Parker’s Roadway System
U L L E V I G
U L L E V I G
The primary roadways in the vicinity of the site include:
 Motsenbocker Road. This north-south collector roadway extends from Clarke Farms
Drive to Stroh Road, a distance of approximately 3.3 miles. The roadway consists of a
basic two-lane cross section in the vicinity of the school site, with a posted speed limit of
35 miles per hour (MPH). In the future, Motsenbocker Road is envisioned as a
Residential Boulevard Collector adjacent to the school site. This Town of Parker
standard cross section includes one through-lane per direction, plus a raised center
median providing left-turn storage at intersections.
 Mainstreet. This east-west arterial roadway extends from Chambers Road to Douglas
County Road 1 east of Parker. West of Chambers Road, Mainstreet continues to I-25
and beyond as Ridgegate Parkway. In the vicinity of the intersection with Motsenbocker
Road, the basic cross section on Mainstreet includes four through lanes with a raised
center median and auxiliary laneage at major intersections. The posted speed limit is
40 MPH. The intersection of Mainstreet and Motsenbocker Road is currently signalized.
 Paoli Way. This two-lane local residential street extends west from Motsenbocker Road,
serving residential uses adjacent to the northern site boundary. East of Motsenbocker
Road, this street continues as Haswell Drive. The intersection at Motsenbocker Road is
currently unsignalized, with STOP sign control on the eastbound and westbound
approaches. The speed limit on Paoli Way is unposted.
 Neutowne Parkway. This two-lane collector roadway intersects Motsenbocker Road
from the west approximately 1,000 feet south of the proposed primary site access. This
roadway serves existing and planned residential development. The intersection at
Motsenbocker Road is currently unsignalized, with STOP sign control on the eastbound
approach. The speed limit on Neutowne Parkway is posted 25 MPH.
Traffic counts were recently conducted in the vicinity of the American Academy site. The counts
included weekday AM and PM peak hour turning movement counts at key intersections, per
Town of Parker direction. See Appendix A for count data sheets.
For the purposes of this analysis, the count times were chosen to coincide with the peak hours
of school activity. The morning peak of student drop-off activity would coincide with the peak of
adjacent street commuter traffic, typically one hour between 7:00 and 9:00 AM. The afternoon
peak of student pick-up activity would occur between 2:00 and 4:00 PM, which is somewhat
earlier than the typical adjacent street PM peak hour.
Figure 3 depicts the existing traffic volumes, intersection geometrics and traffic control, and
intersection Level of Service (LOS) results. See Appendix B for SYNCHRO LOS worksheets.
As shown on Figure 3, Motsenbocker Road currently experiences approximately 2,910 vehicles
per day (VPD) adjacent to the school site. Daily traffic volumes along Mainstreet are estimated
to range between about 17,800 and 20,200 VPD.
LOS is a qualitative measure of traffic operational conditions, based on roadway capacity and
motorist delay. The 2000 Highway Capacity Manual defines six levels of service, ranging from A
to F, with LOS A representing the best possible operating conditions and LOS F representing
over-capacity, or congested conditions. In urbanized areas, LOS D is typically considered to be
acceptable for peak hour traffic operations. As indicated on Figure 3, existing traffic operations
in the vicinity of the American Academy site are acceptable, at LOS C or better, during the peak
U L L E V I G
Specific trip generation rates for charter schools are unavailable from standard resources, such
as the Institute of Transportation Engineers (ITE) Trip Generation. Therefore, to establish trip
rates for the American Academy analysis, traffic data were collected at the existing American
Academy Charter School in the City of Castle Pines. Appendix C includes traffic count data.
The existing school has a current enrollment population of 862, with 840 students in attendance
on May 18, 2012, when the data were collected. Trip generation rates on a per-student basis
were calculated by applying the attendance information to the traffic counts. Table 1
summarizes the resultant trip generation rates. ITE rates for K–8 private schools are included

As indicated in Table 1, the calculated rates for the existing American Academy compare very
well with the ITE rates for private schools. Because the calculated rates are specific to the
actual proposed use, they have been used to estimate the trip generation potential for the
proposed American Academy on Motsenbocker Road. Because the school counts did not
include a daily traffic volume count at the school, the proportion of AM trips to daily trips
calculated from the ITE rates was used to estimate the daily trip generation of the proposed
school. Per ITE, the daily rate is approximately 3.00 times the AM peak hour rate. Table 2

text.b: Trip Generation Analysis – American Academy (Motsenbocker Road Site)

page.text: As indicated in Table 2, the proposed school is expected to generate approximately 765 vehicle
trips during the AM peak hour and about 545 trips during the PM peak hour. The estimated daily
trip generation potential would be about 2,300 trips.

the proposed school would contribute an additional 1,150 VPD to Motsenbocker Road adjacent

U L L E V I G
Background traffic represents the level of traffic activity that would be present on area roadways
regardless of the proposed American Academy. Because the school is expected to be
operational within the near term, the existing traffic volumes (previously presented on Figure 3)
were used as background traffic volumes for the Short Range Future scenario.
For the Long Range Future (year 2030), traffic volume projections were extracted from the
Town’s 2006 Roadway System Evaluation. Traffic volumes specific to Neutowne Parkway were
based on development buildout projections contained in the report entitled Olde Town at Parker
Traffic Impact Analysis, Felsburg Holt & Ullevig, 2003. For the purposes of this analysis, a
planned extension of Todd Drive (located south of the site) that would connect Motsenbocker
Road to Jordan Road, was evaluated relative to the 2030 traffic projections.
modeling results indicate that approximately 2/3 of the volumes projected in the 2006 model
would use the Todd Drive extension, thereby greatly reducing the potential traffic volumes along
Motsenbocker Road in the vicinity of the school site. The Long Range Future background
The Long Range Future background scenario also includes an estimate of traffic volumes
generated by anticipated development along the east side of Motsenbocker Road opposite the
American Academy school site. This currently vacant site consists of about 45 acres, and is
envisioned to accommodate a senior housing center. Considering 50 percent detached/50
percent attached mix of senior residential uses on this site, and based on estimated densities of
about 6 units per acre (detached) and 10 units per acre (attached) units, a total of 360 dwelling
units are estimated. Table 3 summarizes the trip generation analysis for the senior housing

Figure 5 illustrates the resultant Long Range Future traffic projections. As shown,
Motsenbocker Road background volumes would increase to approximately 3,650 VPD adjacent
to the school site. Daily background traffic volumes along Mainstreet are projected to range
between about 28,800 and 32,800 VPD by the year 2030. The intersection geometrics and
traffic control as depicted were used as the basis for LOS analyses, the results of which are
summarized on Figure 5 (LOS worksheets are included in Appendix D). Background traffic
operations are projected to remain within the acceptable range, at LOS D or better, during peak
The site-generated traffic volumes (Figure 4) were added to the existing traffic volumes
(Figure 3) to produce the Short Range Future total traffic volumes illustrated on Figure 6. In the
near term, Motsenbocker Road daily volumes would increase to approximately 4,060 VPD
adjacent to the school site. Daily total traffic volumes along Mainstreet would range between
about 18,380 and 20,660 VPD on completion of the school project.
The peak hour traffic volumes, intersection geometrics, and traffic control shown on Figure 6
were used as the basis for LOS analyses (LOS worksheets are included in Appendix E). As
indicated, traffic operations at the existing signalized intersection at Mainstreet/Motsenbocker
Road would remain acceptable, at LOS C during the peak times analyzed. The two existing
unsignalized intersections along Motsenbocker Road (at Paoli Way and Neutowne Parkway)
would also continue to operate at LOS C or better.
At the proposed primary access for the school, however, the outbound left-turn movement
would experience congestion and delays during the morning peak under the anticipated STOP
sign control. The traffic volumes at this access would be insufficient to warrant a traffic signal,
per peak hour criteria contained in FHWA’s Manual on Uniform Traffic Control Devices
(MUTCD) 2009. Appendix F includes signal warrant evaluations.
outbound left-turns only, and would only occur during the AM peak hour. The projected
maximum probable queue would be only six or seven vehicles (queue calculations are
contained in the LOS worksheets), which should not impact on-site circulation in the near term.
As traffic volumes in the area increase over time, however, restricting this access to ¾
movement (left-in/right-in/right-out only) would help mitigate potential traffic safety or operational
The projected turning movements into the school would be sufficient to require auxiliary lanes
along Motsenbocker Road. A southbound right-turn lane, consisting of 200 feet of storage
length plus 120 feet of transition taper, should be provided, based on the critical AM peak hour
inbound right-turn movement. A northbound left-turn lane should also be provided, to consist of
200 feet of storage length plus 120 feet of transition taper.

Short Range Future Total Traffic Conditions
U L L E V I G
The site-generated traffic volumes (Figure 4) were added to the year 2030 background traffic
volumes (Figure 5) to produce the Long Range Future total traffic volumes illustrated on
Figure 7. As depicted, Motsenbocker Road daily volumes are projected to be approximately
4,800 VPD adjacent to the school site. Daily total traffic volumes along Mainstreet would range
between about 29,380 and 33,260 VPD in the Long Range Future.
The peak hour traffic volumes, intersection geometrics, and traffic control shown on Figure 7
were used as the basis for LOS analyses (LOS worksheets are included in Appendix E). As
indicated, traffic operations at the existing signalized intersection at Mainstreet/Motsenbocker
Road would remain acceptable, at LOS C during the peak times analyzed.
Unsignalized traffic operations along Motsenbocker Road, would also remain generally
acceptable. At the site access, however, congestion and delays for outbound left-turns would
continue for AM peak hour operations. Traffic volumes at this intersection would remain
insufficient to satisfy peak hour signal warrant criteria per the MUTCD. The projected
congestion would only affect outbound left-turns from the school access. Vehicle queues
extending back into the site would remain at approximately six vehicles, which would not be
expected to affect on-site circulation and student drop-off operations. Therefore, traffic
conditions should be monitored over time, and restriction to ¾ movement be considered when
safety or operational conditions dictate. This action would necessitate similar restriction for the
senior housing center access opposite the site; however, alternative routing for the senior
housing center traffic would be available at the southern access to Motsenbocker Road.
As a part of the data collection at the American Academy Charter School in Castle Pines,
vehicle queues were recorded during the critical afternoon peak activity period. The maximum
queue length was 2,580 feet. Using a typical vehicle length of 20 to 25 feet, this equates to a
vehicle stacking requirement of approximately 103 to 129 vehicles.
Comparing the existing enrollment of 862 students at the existing American Academy relative to
the proposed 900 student projection at the proposed school, a stacking requirement of
2,693 feet, or 107 to 135 vehicles is obtained. The current site plan concept for American
Academy (see Figure 2) indicates approximately 2,919 feet for stacking, equating to between
about 116 and 146 vehicles. Therefore, the on-site stacking capacity would be sufficient to
accommodate the potential queues associated with the proposed school.
Long Range Future Total Traffic Conditions
U L L E V I G
The American Academy is proposing a new K–8 charter school in Parker to accommodate
approximately 900 students. The school site is located along the west side of Motsenbocker
Road, to the south of Mainstreet. Site vehicular access would be via two driveways, one of
which would be for emergency use only. The primary access would be located approximately
650 feet south of Paoli Way, a local residential street. The traffic impacts of school generated
traffic were evaluated under both Short Range Future and Long Range Future scenarios. In
general, the existing roadway system would have sufficient reserve capacity to accommodate
the addition of school-related traffic. Relative to this, the following summarize the findings and
 Based on data collected at the existing American Academy charter school in Castle
Pines, and referencing standard ITE rates, the proposed American Academy Charter
School would generate approximately 2,300 vehicle trips on a daily basis, with 765 trips
during the AM peak hour and about 545 trips during the PM peak hour.
 At the intersection of Mainstreet and Motsenbocker Road, the existing signalized traffic
control would provide acceptable operational conditions (LOS C) through the projected
 At the school’s primary access, the STOP controlled outbound left-turn movement would
be at LOS F during AM peak hour operations in both future scenarios. The projected
traffic volumes at this intersection would be insufficient to warrant a traffic signal. Any
congestion resulting from this condition would remain on-site and would not impact
mainline operations along Motsenbocker Road. On-site queuing is expected to be seven
vehicles or less, which would not be expected to impact site circulation. However, due to
the potential for congestion, it is recommended that traffic conditions at this access be
monitored over time, and restriction to ¾ movement be considered when safety or
operational conditions dictate. This action would necessitate similar restriction for the
senior housing center access opposite the site (alternative routing for the senior housing
center traffic would be available at the southern access to Motsenbocker Road).
 A planned extension of Todd Drive (located south of the site) that would connect
Motsenbocker Road to Jordan Road, would greatly reduce the potential traffic volumes
along Motsenbocker Road between Todd Drive and Mainstreet. This improvement would
likely postpone the need for any potential access restrictions at the school.
 The projected turning movements into the school would be sufficient to require auxiliary
lanes along Motsenbocker Road at the primary site access. A southbound right-turn
lane, consisting of 200 feet of storage length plus 120 feet of transition taper, should be
provided, based on the critical AM peak hour inbound right-turn movement. A
northbound left-turn lane should also be provided, to consist of 200 feet of storage length
 Based on data collected at the existing school in Castle Pines, the proposed school
would generate queues of up to 129 vehicles during the critical PM peak hour of student
pick-up activity. The site plan concept allows up to approximately 146 waiting vehicles to
be stored on-site; therefore, vehicle queues would remain on-site and would not be
expected to affect mainline traffic operations along Motsenbocker Road.
